---
// diagram-transport-comparison — Chapter 094 Lesson 7, "Indexes and N+1 in
// production", connection-pool section.
//
// The section's claim: the common read path mostly *designs away* the pool
// problem, because the two Neon transports hold connections in different places.
// This figure makes that difference visible by laying the two transports out as
// two parallel left→right lanes that end at the same Postgres compute:
//
//   HTTP lane (the default):
//     Serverless function ──(one-shot query over HTTP)──▶ Neon SQL-API proxy
//       └ annotated "holds no persistent connection"    (holds its own pre-warmed pool)
//     proxy ──▶ Postgres compute
//   ↑ the proxy OWNS the pool — your function holds nothing. GREEN: the safe path.
//
//   WebSocket lane:
//     App server / function ──(WebSocket Pool)──▶ Postgres compute   (direct, no proxy)
//       └ annotated "holds N connections"
//   ↑ your app holds the connections — a wide fan-out can exhaust them.
//     AMBER: the path where pool sizing comes back to bite.
//
// The contrast is structural: the HTTP lane routes through a proxy box that owns
// pooling; the WebSocket lane goes straight to compute with the app holding the
// connections. That's why the proxy box exists only in the top lane.
//
// Built with <ArrowDiagram> (LeaderLine) because each box is two-line custom HTML
// (a title + a muted under-label) and the per-lane semantic coloring carries the
// meaning — D2/Mermaid plain-label boxes wouldn't. Arrows are positioned from
// document.body, so the wrapping <Figure> MUST be expandable={false}: relocating
// the body into the lightbox breaks the leader lines.
//
// Each arrow stays within its own row (right→left between adjacent boxes), so no
// arrow crosses lanes and the labels float cleanly in the gaps. labelOffset lifts
// each label above its wire.

import Figure from '../../../figures/Figure.astro';
import ArrowDiagram from '../../../figures/ArrowDiagram.astro';

// Mid-tone accents reused verbatim in light + dark.
const HTTP_GREEN = '#16a34a'; // green-600 — the path that sidesteps the pool
const WS_AMBER = '#d97706'; // amber-600 — the path where pool sizing bites

const arrows = [
	// HTTP lane: function → proxy → compute. The query travels over stateless HTTP.
	{
		from: 'tc-fn',
		to: 'tc-proxy',
		label: 'one-shot query over HTTP',
		color: HTTP_GREEN,
		startSocket: 'right',
		endSocket: 'left',
		startSocketGravity: [70, 0],
		endSocketGravity: [-70, 0],
		labelOffset: [0, -34],
	},
	{
		from: 'tc-proxy',
		to: 'tc-compute-http',
		color: HTTP_GREEN,
		startSocket: 'right',
		endSocket: 'left',
		startSocketGravity: [60, 0],
		endSocketGravity: [-60, 0],
	},
	// WebSocket lane: app → compute directly, the app holding the connections.
	{
		from: 'tc-app',
		to: 'tc-compute-ws',
		label: 'WebSocket Pool',
		color: WS_AMBER,
		startSocket: 'right',
		endSocket: 'left',
		startSocketGravity: [80, 0],
		endSocketGravity: [-80, 0],
		labelOffset: [0, -34],
	},
];
---

<Figure expandable={false}>
	<ArrowDiagram arrows={arrows}>
		<div class="tc not-content">
			<div class="tc-lane">
				<div class="tc-tag" style={`color: ${HTTP_GREEN};`}>HTTP — the default</div>
				<div class="tc-row">
					<div class="tc-box" id="tc-fn">
						<span class="tc-title">Serverless function</span>
						<span class="tc-under">holds no persistent connection</span>
					</div>
					<div class="tc-box tc-box--accent" id="tc-proxy" style={`--accent: ${HTTP_GREEN};`}>
						<span class="tc-title">Neon SQL-API proxy</span>
						<span class="tc-under">holds its own pre-warmed pool</span>
					</div>
					<div class="tc-box" id="tc-compute-http">
						<span class="tc-title">Postgres compute</span>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="tc-lane">
				<div class="tc-tag" style={`color: ${WS_AMBER};`}>WebSocket</div>
				<div class="tc-row">
					<div class="tc-box tc-box--accent" id="tc-app" style={`--accent: ${WS_AMBER};`}>
						<span class="tc-title">App server / function</span>
						<span class="tc-under">holds N connections</span>
					</div>
					<div class="tc-box" id="tc-compute-ws">
						<span class="tc-title">Postgres compute</span>
						<span class="tc-under">pool sizing matters here</span>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
	</ArrowDiagram>
	<Fragment slot="caption">
		Two transports to the same database. Over **HTTP**, Neon's proxy owns the pool, so your
		function holds nothing. Over the **WebSocket Pool**, your app holds the connections — and a
		wide fan-out can exhaust them.
	</Fragment>
</Figure>

<style>
	.tc {
		display: flex;
		flex-direction: column;
		gap: 36px;
		margin: 0;
		padding: 18px 4px 10px;
		font-family:
			ui-sans-serif, system-ui, -apple-system, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, sans-serif;
	}

	.tc-lane {
		display: flex;
		flex-direction: column;
		gap: 10px;
		margin: 0;
	}

	.tc-tag {
		font-size: 0.7rem;
		font-weight: 700;
		letter-spacing: 0.04em;
		text-transform: uppercase;
		margin: 0;
	}

	.tc-row {
		display: flex;
		flex-wrap: nowrap;
		align-items: center;
		gap: 96px;
		margin: 0;
	}

	.tc-box {
		box-sizing: border-box;
		display: flex;
		flex-direction: column;
		align-items: center;
		gap: 3px;
		flex: 0 1 auto;
		padding: 11px 16px;
		border-radius: 10px;
		border: 1px solid var(--sl-color-gray-5, #cbd5e1);
		background: var(--sl-color-bg, transparent);
		text-align: center;
		margin: 0;
	}

	.tc-box--accent {
		border-color: var(--accent);
		box-shadow: inset 0 0 0 1px var(--accent);
	}

	.tc-title {
		font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, Monaco, Consolas, monospace;
		font-size: 0.84rem;
		font-weight: 600;
		line-height: 1.2;
		white-space: nowrap;
		color: var(--sl-color-white, #1e293b);
		margin: 0;
	}

	.tc-under {
		font-size: 0.66rem;
		line-height: 1.2;
		white-space: nowrap;
		color: var(--sl-color-gray-3, #64748b);
		margin: 0;
	}

	/* Narrow viewports: stack the boxes in each lane; right→left sockets degrade to
	   vertical arcs between stacked boxes — readable, labels still float in gaps. */
	@media (max-width: 720px) {
		.tc-row {
			flex-direction: column;
			gap: 52px;
			align-items: stretch;
		}
		.tc-box {
			width: min(20rem, 100%);
		}
	}
</style>
